    'title' => 'Introduction To Developing Fireworks Extensions (They’re Just JavaScript!)',
    'content' => '<p>One of the most powerful features of Adobe Fireworks is that you can extend its functionality. Almost anything you can do through Fireworks’ interface &#8212; and even some things that you can’t &#8212; can also be achieved by writing a simple JavaScript extension.</p>

<figure><a href="http://www.smashingmagazine.com/2014/06/04/introduction-to-developing-fireworks-extensions-theyre-just-javascript/"><img src="http://www.smashingmagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/05/02-specctr-panel-opt.png" alt="Introduction To Developing Fireworks Extensions (They’re Just JavaScript!)"></a></figure>

<p><strong>Fireworks extensions are of two main types: commands and command panels</strong>. If you find yourself repeatedly performing a tedious task, you could write a command to automate the process and save yourself a lot of time. Alternatively, if you are missing a particular feature that would improve your workflow, you could write a more complex extension &#8212; a command panel &#8212; to implement it.</p><p>The post <a rel="nofollow" href="http://www.smashingmagazine.com/2014/06/04/introduction-to-developing-fireworks-extensions-theyre-just-javascript/">Introduction To Developing Fireworks Extensions (They&#8217;re Just JavaScript!)</a> appeared first on <a rel="nofollow" href="http://www.smashingmagazine.com">Smashing Magazine</a>.</p>
',
